WEBVTT

00:06.933 --> 00:09.367
GEORGE: If I'm agreeable,
they'll ask Menzies

00:09.367 --> 00:12.067
to add me to our diplomatic
staff in Israel.

00:12.067 --> 00:14.033
We met on a ship,

00:14.033 --> 00:17.833
so as we're about to embark on
the next phase in our lives...

00:20.033 --> 00:25.633
Christmas here, then Hanukkah,
New Year's, then...

00:25.633 --> 00:27.433
The 3rd of January.

00:27.433 --> 00:30.033
So the idea came from Jack,
really.

00:30.033 --> 00:33.333
It's in some ways an extension
of the women's clinic

00:33.333 --> 00:36.033
and Douglas' refuge.

00:36.033 --> 00:40.900
A place for single women,
like Anna and Carolyn,

00:40.900 --> 00:43.200
women who might need somewhere
to give birth.

00:43.200 --> 00:44.700
I'd like us to be together.

00:44.700 --> 00:46.133
But if you're up
in the big smoke...

00:46.133 --> 00:47.467
You could come up.

00:47.467 --> 00:51.033
And occasionally...
this would be my weekender.

00:51.033 --> 00:53.967
OLIVIA: Andrew wanted to
telephone, but...

00:53.967 --> 00:55.300
I wanted to tell you in person.

00:55.300 --> 00:56.733
It's beautiful.

00:56.733 --> 00:59.300
[ Gasps ]
Happy, happy mother!

00:59.300 --> 01:02.100
JACK: There are some blokes
that meet up at the clinic.

01:02.100 --> 01:05.066
What they've said to me is
tell us what needs fixing,

01:05.066 --> 01:07.400
what you need, and they'll do
their best to see it done.

01:07.400 --> 01:08.933
Charity.

01:08.933 --> 01:10.167
It works both ways.

01:10.167 --> 01:11.600
Jack, I can explain!

01:11.600 --> 01:12.900
-Well, so can I.
-Please --

01:12.900 --> 01:14.667
You've had one foot out the door
ever since we met!

01:14.667 --> 01:16.600
-Please!
-That's it!

01:16.600 --> 01:19.400
PRUDENCE: If she's so miserable,
perhaps she should go back.

01:19.400 --> 01:21.300
Without his changing
significantly,

01:21.300 --> 01:22.467
what would be the point?

01:22.467 --> 01:23.967
Bad enough the Japs
cut my balls off.

01:23.967 --> 01:26.400
The woman I love
just did it all over again,

01:26.400 --> 01:29.200
everything rationalized
by her standard old accusation

01:29.200 --> 01:30.233
that I am in a rut.

01:30.233 --> 01:31.400
I think you are.

01:31.400 --> 01:33.667
-Enough, all right?
-We both have been.

01:33.667 --> 01:37.567
I think you have to do
something big, Jack,

01:37.567 --> 01:39.700
or you won't be any good
to anyone.

01:39.700 --> 01:42.233
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

01:44.767 --> 01:47.467
[ Indistinct conversations ]

01:47.467 --> 01:49.067
Can I clear, ma'am?

01:49.067 --> 01:50.667
Oh. Is everyone satisfied?

01:50.667 --> 01:52.733
-I'm stuffed.
-David!

01:52.733 --> 01:54.067
GEORGE:
That's not very polite.

01:54.067 --> 01:56.067
You've had
an elegant sufficiency.

01:56.067 --> 01:57.767
Well, I'm stuffed too, mate.

01:57.767 --> 01:59.767
ELIZABETH:
You're not helping, Mr. Briggs.

01:59.767 --> 02:01.333
Full of tucker, me!

02:01.333 --> 02:03.533
SARAH:
Nor are you.

02:03.533 --> 02:06.867
Such stories to tell
my young ladies.

02:06.867 --> 02:08.767
What bounty we've had.

02:08.767 --> 02:12.267
Mind you, I did leave them
well provided for.

02:12.267 --> 02:14.533
Well, if that cake's
anything to go by.

02:14.533 --> 02:16.100
That's yours, yeah?

02:16.100 --> 02:18.433
It is indeed, Mr. Gibbs.

02:18.433 --> 02:20.133
Um, Bernie Charsley
is touch and go.

02:20.133 --> 02:22.800
I should head back and check.
Excuse me.

02:22.800 --> 02:24.200
Surely they'll call you
if they need you.

02:24.200 --> 02:26.400
Better safe than sorry.

02:26.400 --> 02:28.100
It was a great spread.
Thank you.

02:28.100 --> 02:29.367
-Jack?
-Merry Christmas.

02:29.367 --> 02:31.867
Jack, I'll see you before I go?

02:31.867 --> 02:33.133
I mean, no rush.

02:33.133 --> 02:35.333
I'm here a few days.

02:35.333 --> 02:37.267
Yeah. Yeah.

02:37.267 --> 02:40.767
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

02:40.767 --> 02:42.967
Harder knowing they
could be here and they aren't

02:42.967 --> 02:45.933
than knowing there's no way.

02:47.533 --> 02:49.867
It's all right.
I'll go.

02:54.767 --> 02:56.267
[ Birds chirping ]

02:56.267 --> 02:57.800
Jack?

02:57.800 --> 02:59.833
[ Door opens, closes ]

03:05.300 --> 03:08.633
Don't be too proud
to accept company if it helps.

03:08.633 --> 03:11.267
-Come back when Anna's here.
-I appreciate the concern.

03:11.267 --> 03:13.267
-Jack --
-I'm right.

03:13.867 --> 03:15.900
Back to your guests.

03:22.500 --> 03:24.700
[ Music continues ]

03:26.000 --> 03:32.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

03:53.333 --> 03:55.367
[ Engine starts, revs ]

04:01.767 --> 04:03.600
[ Birds chirping ]

04:03.600 --> 04:04.933
[ Laughter ]

04:04.933 --> 04:08.433
PRUDENCE: Oh, I can't think of
a jollier Christmas!

04:08.433 --> 04:12.200
Even Andrew --
usually such a scrooge!

04:12.200 --> 04:14.367
Oh, don't make him ill
after all that food.

04:14.367 --> 04:15.867
He's burning it off!
[ Laughs ]

04:15.867 --> 04:17.833
Bang! Bang!
Got you!

04:17.833 --> 04:18.833
[ Laughs ]

04:18.833 --> 04:21.399
Just because I puked
every Christmas.

04:21.399 --> 04:23.533
Oh, no need to be so vulgar.

04:23.533 --> 04:25.700
-Martini time.
-Oh.

04:25.700 --> 04:28.400
That eggnog was a tad weak.

04:28.400 --> 04:30.800
"Start light" is my motto.

04:30.800 --> 04:33.233
And finish heavy.

04:33.233 --> 04:34.400
As you will.

04:34.400 --> 04:35.667
I have to drive.

04:35.667 --> 04:39.067
Oh.
Then wowser you may be.

04:39.067 --> 04:40.633
Gentlemen?

04:40.633 --> 04:42.333
I don't have to drive.

04:42.333 --> 04:44.467
Prudence offered my old room
for the night.

04:45.067 --> 04:46.367
And Harry.

04:47.333 --> 04:48.500
You sure?

04:48.500 --> 04:51.400
The sheep can look after
themselves for one night.

04:52.500 --> 04:54.267
Two rooms, of course.

04:54.800 --> 04:58.133
But who tiptoes where
when I'm abed is not my concern.

04:58.133 --> 04:59.767
[ Laughter ]

04:59.767 --> 05:01.900
Caro?
Extra fuel?

05:03.400 --> 05:04.433
Caro?

05:04.433 --> 05:06.233
HENRY:
I'd like to propose a toast

05:06.233 --> 05:07.900
to our marvelous host, Prudence.

05:07.900 --> 05:09.867
You can doubt it?

05:12.833 --> 05:16.067
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

05:28.900 --> 05:31.200
Our first Ash Park Hanukkah.

05:31.200 --> 05:33.400
How wonderful.

05:33.400 --> 05:37.733
Now, who would like the shamash?

05:37.733 --> 05:39.067
-Me!
-Oh!

05:39.067 --> 05:40.467
Isn't it ladies first?

05:40.467 --> 05:42.933
Leah doesn't want it.
Do you?

05:42.933 --> 05:43.933
Do you, Leah?

05:43.933 --> 05:46.433
Uh, let me think.

05:46.433 --> 05:47.500
You're teasing.

05:47.500 --> 05:49.067
[ Laughter ]

05:49.067 --> 05:50.167
May anyone participate?

05:50.167 --> 05:52.067
Ah.
Perfect timing.

05:52.067 --> 05:54.700
I've never seen Jewish stuff
before.

05:54.700 --> 05:58.667
David explained over lunch that
it's connected to a miracle.

05:58.667 --> 06:01.733
Yes, that's right.
And Hanukkah is our reminder.

06:01.733 --> 06:03.933
-It's the same day as Christmas?
-This year.

06:03.933 --> 06:05.067
It's on a lunar cycle.

06:05.067 --> 06:06.600
We're glad you could make it.

06:06.600 --> 06:07.667
Me too.

06:07.667 --> 06:10.067
[ Music continues ]

06:12.067 --> 06:17.200
* Baruch Atta adonai *

06:17.200 --> 06:21.600
* Eloheinu melekh ha'olam *

06:21.600 --> 06:26.433
* Asher kid'shanu b'mitzvotav *

06:26.433 --> 06:31.233
* V'tzivanu l'hadlik ner *

06:31.233 --> 06:35.633
* Shel Hanukkah *

06:36.267 --> 06:38.800
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

06:44.300 --> 06:46.133
[ Door opens ]

06:46.133 --> 06:47.800
[ Baby cooing ]

07:00.733 --> 07:02.900
[ Clock ticking ]

07:02.900 --> 07:05.600
[ Footsteps approaching ]

07:07.100 --> 07:08.933
[ Knock on door ]

07:08.933 --> 07:10.367
What did I say?

07:11.833 --> 07:14.367
I don't know.
What did you say?

07:14.367 --> 07:17.867
I'm sorry.
I...I asked for privacy.

07:17.867 --> 07:21.300
I'm sick of people invading
to check up on me.

07:21.300 --> 07:25.067
Well, this little one wanted to
see Grandpapa before Ash Park.

07:26.133 --> 07:28.667
Merry first Christmas,
little one.

07:30.600 --> 07:32.267
How'd you know
I wouldn't still be there?

07:32.267 --> 07:33.933
I telephoned.

07:33.933 --> 07:35.633
They said you'd dashed off.

07:35.633 --> 07:37.200
So you're checking up too?

07:37.767 --> 07:39.633
Daughter's privilege.

07:40.467 --> 07:42.933
You know we would have been here
all day if you'd asked.

07:43.633 --> 07:45.133
You're here now.

07:46.133 --> 07:48.233
-Aren't you?
-[ Baby cooing ]

07:51.300 --> 07:53.233
How was it?

07:53.767 --> 07:56.967
It was all very dull.
Nothing special.

07:57.433 --> 07:58.333
You?

07:58.333 --> 08:00.500
Oh.
Don't worry about me.

08:00.500 --> 08:02.067
But I do.

08:02.533 --> 08:04.333
Yeah, you and the rest.

08:06.167 --> 08:08.167
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

08:08.167 --> 08:10.833
Lot of grog around at Christmas.

08:11.400 --> 08:12.633
You wouldn't.

08:29.433 --> 08:31.667
Took everything I had.

08:31.667 --> 08:33.533
But you didn't.

08:36.500 --> 08:38.500
The firsts without her
are hardest.

08:38.500 --> 08:41.299
And the first New Year is next.
I'll have to watch it.

08:41.299 --> 08:43.866
-I'll keep an eye on you.
-You go wherever you want.

08:44.767 --> 08:47.233
Elaine wants to see in the '60s
with Grandpapa,

08:47.233 --> 08:49.433
so we'll all be together.

08:49.433 --> 08:50.933
I'm fine.

08:50.933 --> 08:53.500
[ Music continues ]

08:53.500 --> 08:55.700
[ Insects chirping ]

09:01.767 --> 09:03.800
DAVID:
It's too early!

09:03.800 --> 09:06.200
Christmas, Hanukkah,
and Shabbat.

09:06.200 --> 09:08.067
It's quite enough for one day.

09:08.067 --> 09:10.333
Well, you're not going to bed.

09:10.333 --> 09:12.133
Well, I'm not 6.

09:12.133 --> 09:13.933
How about if I read to you

09:13.933 --> 09:15.900
before I go back
to Mrs. Collins?

09:15.900 --> 09:17.733
Bomba the Jungle Boy?

09:17.733 --> 09:18.800
Whatever you like.

09:18.800 --> 09:21.067
Get changed.
We'll be in soon.

09:22.533 --> 09:24.733
You should consider
pediatric nursing.

09:24.733 --> 09:26.367
You have the touch.

09:26.367 --> 09:27.600
I might.

09:27.600 --> 09:29.933
I can't wait to start
proper training.

09:29.933 --> 09:31.800
New decade, new career.

09:31.800 --> 09:33.667
And Sydney.

09:34.633 --> 09:36.333
Thank you.

09:37.800 --> 09:39.300
Oh.

09:39.833 --> 09:41.667
For everything.

09:42.367 --> 09:45.067
Your Aunt Miriam would be
so proud.

09:46.067 --> 09:47.733
You think?

09:48.433 --> 09:49.533
I am.

09:55.167 --> 09:58.667
Now, Roy will need extra hands
whilst we're away.

09:58.667 --> 10:00.933
Is there anyone at the refuge
who might suit?

10:00.933 --> 10:02.800
Especially from the men
you've encouraged.

10:02.800 --> 10:05.200
Mr. Briggs would train
any you choose.

10:05.200 --> 10:07.167
Well, best check with him first.

10:07.700 --> 10:10.400
Well, there's not an ounce
of prejudice in the man.

10:10.400 --> 10:12.067
I mean, look at him with you.

10:12.067 --> 10:15.333
Fine with one
doesn't mean fine with all.

10:15.333 --> 10:18.700
I mean, there's a fella who,
handled wrong,

10:18.700 --> 10:20.467
uh, he could jack up.

10:20.467 --> 10:23.133
Well, I'm sure Roy would manage
if he was briefed.

10:23.133 --> 10:26.067
Perhaps introduce me to him
next time I'm at the refuge.

10:26.067 --> 10:28.033
And you must come by
the hospital.

10:28.033 --> 10:29.300
It's near completion.

10:29.300 --> 10:32.267
I'm keen that it's not
just for white girls.

10:32.267 --> 10:34.433
I need advice
on how best to effect that.

10:34.433 --> 10:36.500
Well, you know the aunties.
Ask them.

10:36.500 --> 10:38.100
But I like the idea.

10:39.000 --> 10:40.833
I've been thinking about Jack.

10:40.833 --> 10:42.600
Might get a fire going.

10:42.600 --> 10:44.767
You know, we had our best yarns
that way.

10:44.767 --> 10:47.033
Sarah's right.
He could do with one.

10:47.033 --> 10:49.033
ELIZABETH:
Hm.

10:49.033 --> 10:50.033
Thanks for today.

10:50.033 --> 10:51.433
Oh, it was our pleasure.

10:51.433 --> 10:52.933
And thank you again
for the painting.

10:52.933 --> 10:54.033
I will treasure it.

10:54.033 --> 10:55.300
Might be worth a quid or two
one day.

10:55.300 --> 10:57.700
Oh. Well, it won't be sold
in my lifetime.

10:57.700 --> 10:59.867
I hope you do better with Jack
than we have.

10:59.867 --> 11:01.633
I'll give it a go.

11:04.533 --> 11:07.400
[ Insects chirping ]

11:07.400 --> 11:09.767
[ Fire crackling ]

11:13.133 --> 11:14.967
Missed this.

11:18.267 --> 11:20.633
I'm glad I dragged you out,
then.

11:24.767 --> 11:28.467
Missed just looking
at the sparks...

11:30.067 --> 11:32.200
...simply not saying.

11:34.633 --> 11:37.400
Best way to get saying.

11:42.933 --> 11:45.933
I was stuck
when I first hit Inverness.

11:48.833 --> 11:51.100
But I left a changed man.

11:52.333 --> 11:54.067
Thanks to you.

11:59.067 --> 12:02.933
Sometimes you got to move
to unstick.

12:07.300 --> 12:09.867
First place you think --
Where could you go if you could?

12:11.067 --> 12:12.433
To help.

12:14.267 --> 12:16.433
Tell yourself, not me.

12:18.267 --> 12:20.467
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

12:24.733 --> 12:26.133
Yeah?

12:30.900 --> 12:33.400
[ Exhales sharply ]
Yeah. Yeah.

12:33.933 --> 12:35.700
Then go.

12:37.767 --> 12:40.800
Well, you're bugger-all use
to yourself like this.

12:43.500 --> 12:45.300
Well, are ya?

12:47.467 --> 12:48.967
No.

13:10.267 --> 13:13.267
[ Mid-tempo music playing,
liquid pouring ]

13:13.267 --> 13:17.267
You know, if somebody
had have told me last Christmas

13:17.267 --> 13:21.067
that this would be my Christmas
this Christmas,

13:21.067 --> 13:23.100
I'd have said they're mad.

13:23.767 --> 13:25.300
Love.

13:25.867 --> 13:27.600
Loss.

13:28.767 --> 13:34.067
Fatherhood...and enough warmth
to drown in.

13:34.067 --> 13:36.333
We're all feeling that.

13:36.867 --> 13:39.433
Even though I am worried
about the sheep.

13:39.433 --> 13:41.600
DELIA:
You've got competition, Henry.

13:41.600 --> 13:44.067
He's less woolly
but way better legs.

13:44.067 --> 13:45.900
[ Laughter ]

13:45.900 --> 13:48.233
Oh, too delicious.

13:48.233 --> 13:50.333
He's for keeping.

13:54.500 --> 13:56.533
[ Voice breaking ]
I miss him.

13:58.133 --> 14:00.233
[ Music continues ]

14:01.333 --> 14:05.267
Oh, sorry.
I miss him so much.

14:08.200 --> 14:10.700
[ Sobs ]

14:10.700 --> 14:12.600
I'm sorry.

14:20.067 --> 14:22.267
[ Insects chirping ]

14:27.600 --> 14:31.233
Now, Jack...I might leave you
to tell them.

14:32.067 --> 14:34.133
You sure?

14:34.133 --> 14:35.767
See you tomorrow.

14:36.233 --> 14:38.833
You've got guts.
I'll say that.

14:44.867 --> 14:46.800
So tomorrow we have two candles.

14:46.800 --> 14:51.067
You let them burn for half an
hour and stay, sharing company.

14:51.067 --> 14:54.333
It's one of our most joyous
celebrations.

14:54.333 --> 14:56.900
Not sure what my news does
for the joy.

14:57.867 --> 15:00.267
Frank got me thinking.

15:00.767 --> 15:02.800
Thanks for not giving up.

15:02.800 --> 15:05.100
I thought another voice.

15:05.633 --> 15:07.767
JACK:
Like you said back when,

15:07.767 --> 15:11.700
your war damage made you scared
to settle...

15:13.067 --> 15:14.200
...me to move.

15:16.333 --> 15:20.100
I'll be heading off, uh,
not long after you two.

15:21.733 --> 15:26.233
I'll make my way back to the --
the place that scares me most.

15:29.500 --> 15:31.267
Might help
clear a few things up.

15:31.267 --> 15:32.767
Where are you going?

15:32.767 --> 15:33.967
Back?

15:36.333 --> 15:41.067
To...where it started, where...

15:41.900 --> 15:43.600
...where it happened.

15:44.767 --> 15:47.767
Burma.
Um...

15:48.300 --> 15:49.667
Where they did what they did.

15:53.233 --> 15:54.633
You get it.

15:54.633 --> 15:57.367
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

16:00.067 --> 16:02.700
I've never had the courage.

16:03.167 --> 16:05.667
I wonder if I ever will.

16:06.800 --> 16:08.833
It's very brave, Jack.

16:11.100 --> 16:13.067
Well, it's kill or cure.

16:18.267 --> 16:20.800
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

16:25.133 --> 16:27.267
[ Insects chirping ]

16:27.267 --> 16:29.800
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

16:32.667 --> 16:34.933
Perhaps we have an artist
in the family.

16:34.933 --> 16:36.800
You never know.

16:38.333 --> 16:40.267
Thank you for thinking of him.

16:40.267 --> 16:43.167
I couldn't turn up to Christmas
without something for the kid.

16:43.167 --> 16:46.100
-[ Clock chiming ]
-That's the half-hour.

16:47.967 --> 16:50.700
So you sit every night
for a half-hour and just gab?

16:50.700 --> 16:53.100
Yes, while the candles burn.

16:53.100 --> 16:55.167
-This Israel thing.
-Mm-hmm?

16:55.867 --> 16:58.333
Uh, the Jews were tossed out,
you say.

16:58.333 --> 17:01.100
By the Romans -- 135 A.D.

17:01.100 --> 17:03.467
And a man had a dream
that they were going back again?

17:03.467 --> 17:07.067
Theodor Herzl,
some sixty-odd years ago.

17:07.067 --> 17:08.166
Seemed impossible.

17:08.166 --> 17:09.933
Even some of the Jews
called him mad.

17:09.933 --> 17:13.099
There it is, now.
Israel.

17:14.067 --> 17:16.567
It happened.
Gives a man hope.

17:16.567 --> 17:17.900
How so?

17:17.900 --> 17:19.833
Well, 2,000 years
for your mob

17:19.833 --> 17:21.833
and only 200 years for ours.

17:21.833 --> 17:23.833
You found your way
out of the oppression,

17:23.833 --> 17:26.400
so maybe there's light at the
end of the tunnel for my mob.

17:26.400 --> 17:28.500
Any help I can ever be
in Canberra.

17:28.500 --> 17:31.633
And any I can give.
We've shown we make a good team.

17:31.633 --> 17:33.200
They're the way, I reckon.

17:33.767 --> 17:36.067
See that they see what's right.

17:36.067 --> 17:37.533
The new generation.

17:39.233 --> 17:41.067
Our best hope.

17:42.467 --> 17:44.633
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

17:45.867 --> 17:48.567
I made so bold
as to prepare a cold collation.

17:48.567 --> 17:50.100
Uh, no need.
Thank you.

17:50.100 --> 17:52.500
You barely picked at your food
yesterday.

17:52.500 --> 17:53.667
Watching, were you?

17:53.667 --> 17:57.267
And will do, perhaps selfishly.

17:57.267 --> 18:00.067
This hospital is bursting
into life.

18:00.067 --> 18:03.300
Mr. Rowe, an excellent surgeon,

18:03.300 --> 18:06.867
has his eye on one
of my young ladies, you know.

18:06.867 --> 18:08.700
And your men's group.

18:08.700 --> 18:10.967
None of my earlier fears
have been realized.

18:10.967 --> 18:12.067
Told you.

18:12.067 --> 18:13.567
You did.

18:14.533 --> 18:18.500
A whisper tells me that you
may be leaving us for a time.

18:18.500 --> 18:20.067
Oh, jungle drums.

18:20.067 --> 18:24.800
Emma and Leah, home with news,
shared as interest, not gossip.

18:27.267 --> 18:28.800
Of course.

18:29.567 --> 18:32.733
Uh, I am off for a bit,
to clear my head.

18:32.733 --> 18:35.300
Mm-hmm.
Well deserved.

18:36.933 --> 18:39.100
May I make an observation,
Doctor?

18:39.633 --> 18:40.900
Go for it.

18:40.900 --> 18:45.067
You touch people's lives
in ways you will never know.

18:45.600 --> 18:49.300
And if what I hear is true,
that will be confirmed tomorrow.

18:49.300 --> 18:51.967
I say no more
should it not transpire.

18:51.967 --> 18:55.833
But should it, it will prove
your worth to Inverness

18:55.833 --> 18:59.067
more than any words
that I can offer.

18:59.067 --> 19:00.633
Enough.
Eat.

19:03.267 --> 19:06.233
You're greatly cared for,
Doctor.

19:07.633 --> 19:09.333
Uh, Doris.

19:11.767 --> 19:13.233
So are you.

19:13.233 --> 19:14.667
Ah.

19:15.333 --> 19:16.567
Hm!

19:18.800 --> 19:20.633
What on earth prompted it?

19:20.633 --> 19:24.433
Frank Gibbs worked
some fireside magic.

19:24.433 --> 19:26.167
He's geed him on.

19:26.167 --> 19:28.100
To?

19:28.100 --> 19:30.467
Examine his past --

19:30.467 --> 19:34.233
I hope towards the end
of resolving your futures.

19:34.233 --> 19:37.567
Or his, singular, without me.

19:37.567 --> 19:40.733
Carolyn, Jack wants to find
a way back to you.

19:40.733 --> 19:43.233
This is him searching for one.

19:43.233 --> 19:45.167
Returning to that
monstrous place helps?

19:45.167 --> 19:48.867
Well, perhaps a form
of shock therapy.

19:50.067 --> 19:53.067
And that, given my adopted role
of Switzerland

19:53.067 --> 19:56.200
in family matters,
is all I'll say.

19:58.400 --> 19:59.667
Anna's thoughts?

20:00.367 --> 20:03.900
Equally diplomatic,
equally hopeful.

20:04.933 --> 20:06.833
Have hope.

20:06.833 --> 20:09.567
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

20:09.567 --> 20:11.600
[ Birds chirping ]

20:15.433 --> 20:18.200
ANNA: He's getting more famous
all the time.

20:18.200 --> 20:20.533
-Two hits!
-I meant to show you yesterday.

20:20.533 --> 20:22.400
-How does it feel?
-What?

20:22.400 --> 20:24.433
Your old boyfriend being a star.

20:24.433 --> 20:25.633
Ah.

20:25.633 --> 20:28.167
Are you going to look him up
in Sydney?

20:29.000 --> 20:30.233
Why?

20:30.233 --> 20:32.433
-He gave you a friendship ring.
-We were kids.

20:32.433 --> 20:35.267
-You're not ancient.
-[ Vehicle approaching ]

20:35.267 --> 20:37.533
Too much has changed.

20:38.233 --> 20:39.467
Church.

20:39.467 --> 20:40.733
Are you going?

20:40.733 --> 20:42.833
I might spare the congregation
Elaine's singing.

20:42.833 --> 20:44.300
Yeah.

20:45.400 --> 20:48.500
What Roy's doing for you,
it's amazing.

20:48.500 --> 20:50.233
I know.

20:50.233 --> 20:53.000
I always thought
that Mum loved him more than me,

20:53.000 --> 20:55.633
but...now I know
why she loved him.

20:55.633 --> 20:57.167
-[ Horn honks ]
-Emma!

20:57.167 --> 20:58.700
Coming!
Bye.

20:58.700 --> 21:00.600
[ Chuckles ]

21:00.600 --> 21:02.267
[ Baby cooing ]

21:02.267 --> 21:04.200
We're going to stay in touch
in the city.

21:04.200 --> 21:06.900
Good.
It can be a lonely place.

21:10.433 --> 21:13.433
Do you think I'd be stupid
to try and see him?

21:13.433 --> 21:14.467
Larry?

21:14.467 --> 21:16.233
Yes.

21:16.233 --> 21:17.733
I listen to your serial.

21:17.733 --> 21:21.067
I...I know it's about you.

21:21.600 --> 21:23.500
You loved your husband,
and you were different,

21:23.500 --> 21:25.333
and that didn't work out.

21:25.333 --> 21:27.500
Works out in the serial.
Keep listening.

21:30.433 --> 21:32.267
We could end up the same.

21:32.267 --> 21:33.633
Or not.

21:33.633 --> 21:36.400
One thing I do know is
I wouldn't be who I am today

21:36.400 --> 21:37.767
if I hadn't married Gino.

21:37.767 --> 21:39.067
And...

21:40.967 --> 21:42.633
Well, I wouldn't change a thing.

21:44.667 --> 21:47.067
I'm sure Larry would love
to see you.

21:47.067 --> 21:48.533
-You think?
-Yes.

21:48.533 --> 21:51.967
And if not, you won't spend
your life wondering.

21:51.967 --> 21:54.167
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

21:58.167 --> 22:00.133
[ Laughs ]

22:00.133 --> 22:02.700
[ Typewriter clicking ]

22:02.700 --> 22:05.100
We're taking Georgie to Bondi.

22:05.100 --> 22:06.900
Feel like a dip?

22:08.933 --> 22:09.833
Carolyn?

22:10.400 --> 22:12.567
What?
Oh.

22:12.567 --> 22:14.233
Miles away.

22:14.233 --> 22:15.867
Would you like to join us?

22:16.400 --> 22:18.433
I have to go over some papers
with Delia.

22:18.433 --> 22:19.500
She's coming.

22:20.367 --> 22:22.067
Typical.

22:23.200 --> 22:24.767
Enjoy yourselves.

22:24.767 --> 22:26.967
-You're sure?
-Yes.

22:29.067 --> 22:30.600
Livvy.

22:31.633 --> 22:33.700
It's lovely to see you so happy.

22:34.267 --> 22:37.467
Move your tushie.
Swim will do you good.

22:39.133 --> 22:42.167
I think you're in the doghouse.

22:43.167 --> 22:45.167
I'll meet you out front.

22:45.167 --> 22:47.067
[ Typewriter clicking ]

22:49.067 --> 22:51.067
It's Sunday.

22:51.500 --> 22:53.533
We promised this quote
by tomorrow.

22:53.533 --> 22:55.567
Christmastime.
They'll cut us some slack.

22:55.567 --> 22:57.933
You are so damned cavalier.

23:03.500 --> 23:05.533
I'm sorry.

23:05.533 --> 23:07.467
I understand.

23:15.133 --> 23:22.200
I'd hung on to a sliver of hope
until your collapse.

23:22.900 --> 23:26.867
I accept now I have none.

23:29.467 --> 23:31.533
I am sorry.

23:36.267 --> 23:38.100
You are who you are.

23:38.100 --> 23:40.500
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

23:40.500 --> 23:42.267
Go to him.

23:42.733 --> 23:43.733
[ Sighs ]

23:43.733 --> 23:46.500
When he returns from Burma,
perhaps.

23:46.500 --> 23:49.500
Before.
And no "perhaps."

23:50.100 --> 23:52.267
You wanted him to move.

23:52.267 --> 23:54.400
He might return no different.

23:54.400 --> 23:56.833
He must be wondering
about your reaction.

23:59.133 --> 24:01.800
Something I haven't shared.

24:02.367 --> 24:04.067
I telephoned him.

24:05.667 --> 24:07.167
-When?
-Months back.

24:07.167 --> 24:09.500
The day of the christening.

24:09.500 --> 24:13.800
I told him I could only take you
if he let me.

24:14.933 --> 24:17.467
I thought it might stir him
to action.

24:18.567 --> 24:19.900
Clearly didn't.

24:19.900 --> 24:21.567
Until now.

24:21.567 --> 24:23.800
It must have contributed.

24:25.767 --> 24:30.233
There was pride and anger
in his voice.

24:31.700 --> 24:35.300
You can only be that proud
and that angry

24:35.300 --> 24:37.600
when you love that much.

24:39.667 --> 24:43.267
Somewhat akin to your good self.

24:49.333 --> 24:54.067
For God's sake, woman.
You said you wanted him to move.

24:56.967 --> 24:59.333
[ Music continues ]

25:02.133 --> 25:04.500
[ Birds chirping ]

25:09.833 --> 25:13.067
Well, there's still
a fair few meetings to go.

25:13.067 --> 25:15.567
It'll take a while to organize.

25:15.567 --> 25:17.400
Going to the middle
of the jungle?

25:17.400 --> 25:18.700
I'll bet.

25:19.567 --> 25:22.833
Makes me think I wouldn't mind
going to Kokoda one day,

25:22.833 --> 25:24.700
seeing where my boy went.

25:24.700 --> 25:26.200
I thought he went in Europe.

25:26.200 --> 25:28.333
One did.
I lost them both.

25:28.333 --> 25:29.567
Ruddy hell.

25:29.567 --> 25:32.700
Not much older than you,
either, mate.

25:32.700 --> 25:35.800
I wish the great one had been
the war to end all wars.

25:35.800 --> 25:37.833
Be good if ours was.

25:37.833 --> 25:41.067
The way the commies are going,
it doesn't seem likely.

25:41.067 --> 25:42.933
Yellow bloody peril.

25:43.667 --> 25:47.167
Good topic for today, maybe --
war.

25:48.200 --> 25:50.800
What it takes and --
and what it does.

25:50.800 --> 25:53.333
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

25:54.833 --> 25:56.867
SHEILA:
You don't have to.

25:58.233 --> 26:00.167
A promise is a promise.

26:01.100 --> 26:02.733
I'll be here.

26:06.833 --> 26:08.167
Not easy.

26:10.067 --> 26:12.100
After what those fellas have
done for us,

26:12.100 --> 26:14.433
it's the least you can do.

26:14.433 --> 26:16.633
[ Music continues ]

26:18.267 --> 26:20.767
I used to sit with my mate Bill.

26:20.767 --> 26:22.933
We kept each other
off the booze.

26:22.933 --> 26:25.067
-Poor old Bill.
-Why?

26:26.867 --> 26:29.800
He, uh, he hung himself.

26:29.800 --> 26:31.333
Geez.

26:32.767 --> 26:38.167
I can...understand
how a bloke might.

26:38.733 --> 26:40.733
Stan.

26:40.733 --> 26:46.133
Asked Sheila what she wants
for Christmas, and...

26:46.133 --> 26:47.333
she said this.

26:48.867 --> 26:51.633
Would have been easier
buying her something.

26:52.267 --> 26:54.500
Took me a while to get my head
around it too, mate.

26:54.500 --> 26:56.567
-I'll get a chair.
-Come in.

27:01.167 --> 27:04.367
Not...my idea.

27:04.967 --> 27:06.933
Well, you can bail at any time.

27:07.567 --> 27:09.433
Hope you don't.

27:12.100 --> 27:14.267
I can't promise nothing.

27:14.833 --> 27:16.800
Not asking you to.

27:19.533 --> 27:22.233
[ Music continues ]

27:22.933 --> 27:28.133
DORIS: You touch people's lives
in ways you will never know.

27:30.067 --> 27:32.200
It's a start.

27:33.067 --> 27:35.433
What if I say the wrong things?

27:35.433 --> 27:37.233
Just say what's in your heart.

27:37.233 --> 27:39.600
Oh, I'm so sorry
to drag you into it.

27:39.600 --> 27:41.267
Mm.

27:42.467 --> 27:44.667
Oh, pooh to Switzerland.

27:44.667 --> 27:46.233
I've sat on my thoughts
for months.

27:46.233 --> 27:48.367
You both need a good kick
in the rear.

27:49.867 --> 27:52.233
That wasn't meant to be funny.

27:52.233 --> 27:54.567
"Pooh to Switzerland"?

27:54.567 --> 27:56.500
And a good kick in the rear.

28:00.267 --> 28:02.633
[ Sobs, sighs ]

28:06.200 --> 28:10.533
This offers the hope
you said you wanted.

28:10.533 --> 28:11.567
You fight.

28:11.567 --> 28:13.067
Mm-hmm.

28:18.833 --> 28:21.467
PRIMO: [ Italian accent ]
He will not accept us.

28:21.467 --> 28:23.367
My mama and papa will not.

28:23.367 --> 28:26.267
Only you understand.
We cannot tell.

28:26.267 --> 28:28.933
MARGARET: I will not lie for
you, but I will champion you.

28:28.933 --> 28:32.167
We'll find a way to see
they do accept you.

28:32.167 --> 28:35.067
CHARLOTTE: We had found our ally
in Sister Andrews,

28:35.067 --> 28:37.433
but our battle
was only just beginning.

28:37.433 --> 28:40.067
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

28:40.067 --> 28:41.967
MAN ON RADIO: Be listening
for the next chapter

28:41.967 --> 28:44.533
of "Tender Vines,"
a Gaynor Dobson production

28:44.533 --> 28:47.067
I couldn't convince them
to let Primo speak

28:47.067 --> 28:48.867
with an Australian accent.

28:48.867 --> 28:52.333
To them, Italians all-a speak-a
like-a that.

28:52.333 --> 28:55.800
But then everyone else speaks
with plums in their mouths.

28:55.800 --> 28:57.067
But that's radio.

28:57.067 --> 28:59.233
Your Sister Andrews reminds me
of someone,

28:59.233 --> 29:01.133
but I can't quite work out who.

29:01.900 --> 29:05.667
She's based on a woman we met
on a ship coming home.

29:05.667 --> 29:07.167
She changed all our lives.

29:07.167 --> 29:08.467
Not ringing a bell.

29:09.600 --> 29:11.967
I'm serious.

29:11.967 --> 29:14.733
You made us all far better
than we might have been.

29:15.567 --> 29:17.067
That's a lovely thing to say.

29:17.067 --> 29:19.333
It's true.

29:20.600 --> 29:23.833
I shudder to think
what I might have become.

29:24.333 --> 29:26.700
I'd shut out life.

29:27.867 --> 29:30.133
So it's been a two-way street.

29:30.133 --> 29:32.500
Helping us all find home.

29:33.267 --> 29:35.900
In one form or another.

29:35.900 --> 29:39.133
A place for some,
for some a person,

29:39.133 --> 29:41.067
for the lucky, both.

29:42.567 --> 29:45.767
With two notable exceptions.

29:47.433 --> 29:50.067
You could at least have given
some warning.

29:50.067 --> 29:52.533
You've made a habit
of avoiding me.

29:54.733 --> 29:56.733
You want a divorce, right?

29:56.733 --> 29:59.200
-Not like it's a surprise.
-Don't.

29:59.200 --> 30:01.500
Delia warned me she'd take you.

30:01.967 --> 30:04.033
She should never have said that.

30:04.033 --> 30:05.633
She can't.

30:06.233 --> 30:08.533
I don't want her.

30:08.533 --> 30:10.400
And I don't want a divorce.

30:13.633 --> 30:15.567
Then why are you here?

30:15.567 --> 30:17.300
Haven't we trawled over it
enough?

30:17.300 --> 30:20.633
We've barely spoken for months.

30:20.633 --> 30:22.600
I'm committed to this hospital.

30:23.967 --> 30:25.500
I am doing good.

30:26.267 --> 30:28.100
It's better than anything else
I can do,

30:28.100 --> 30:30.667
and it sure beats running
with your pack.

30:30.667 --> 30:33.433
I didn't come here to fight.

30:38.600 --> 30:40.700
I heard what you're doing.

30:41.933 --> 30:44.067
Where you're going.

30:44.633 --> 30:46.667
I'd like to know why.

30:47.600 --> 30:49.400
You care?

30:50.467 --> 30:52.667
[ Sighs ]

30:52.667 --> 30:53.733
Don't.

30:53.733 --> 30:56.267
Of course I care!

30:57.167 --> 30:59.267
Please.

31:01.067 --> 31:02.533
All right.

31:02.533 --> 31:05.067
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

31:09.567 --> 31:12.433
I was a mess before you came
back into my life.

31:14.233 --> 31:16.400
Been an even bigger one
since you left.

31:19.733 --> 31:21.733
Loving you helped dull
what the war did,

31:21.733 --> 31:23.767
but it's never not there.

31:25.367 --> 31:27.667
It's time I face it head on.

31:29.600 --> 31:33.167
Examine the wounds,
abrade the dead tissue.

31:34.133 --> 31:36.967
And you think going back there
is the way?

31:36.967 --> 31:40.133
It'll be a hard slog,
but going there...

31:41.267 --> 31:47.067
...standing there, feeling...
whatever I'll feel...

31:49.133 --> 31:51.467
...it'll force me
to really address it.

31:53.067 --> 31:55.067
And I haven't.
I just...

31:56.300 --> 31:58.333
...kept pushing it down.

32:00.067 --> 32:02.600
Has it got anything to do
with me?

32:05.100 --> 32:09.367
I'm sorry if that sounds
self-centered, but...has it?

32:09.833 --> 32:11.900
In even the smallest way?

32:14.800 --> 32:18.633
Might some part of you hope
that your journey

32:18.633 --> 32:23.100
somehow...could help get you
past your anger at me?

32:25.300 --> 32:26.567
No.

32:30.467 --> 32:32.633
I think it does.

32:34.300 --> 32:40.700
I think you want to see...
a way past this as much as I do.

32:42.233 --> 32:46.067
[ Voice breaking ]
You hope there's at least...

32:46.067 --> 32:48.833
the seed of an answer there.

32:52.400 --> 32:58.300
I'm here to say...
that I want to go with you.

32:58.300 --> 33:03.067
If you find the answer...
I want to be there.

33:03.633 --> 33:05.833
And if not,
I hope that my sharing it

33:05.833 --> 33:08.833
can somehow take the bitterness
from our lives.

33:11.933 --> 33:18.333
All I know...is that I love you
with all of my heart,

33:18.333 --> 33:21.067
and I can't let you do it alone.

33:32.233 --> 33:35.600
I'll be at Ash Park
until New Year's Day.

33:41.467 --> 33:47.633
Can't we try to use this
to return to each other somehow?

33:49.433 --> 33:52.267
I don't expect an answer now.

33:53.300 --> 33:55.167
Unless you have one.

34:00.567 --> 34:02.100
No.

34:15.867 --> 34:17.900
You know where to find me.

34:21.433 --> 34:23.733
PRUDENCE: There's no need
to run off, surely?

34:23.733 --> 34:28.699
Well, my job here is done,
and whatever's next for Caro,

34:28.699 --> 34:31.567
best I'm out
of her personal life.

34:32.132 --> 34:34.333
We will meet
strictly for business,

34:34.333 --> 34:36.067
should she wish to continue so.

34:36.067 --> 34:41.167
You have brightened Casa Swanson
through more than renovation.

34:41.167 --> 34:44.132
You are a very special woman.

34:45.067 --> 34:47.067
As are you, my dear.

34:48.667 --> 34:51.500
Then it's hi-ho, Silver,
and away.

34:51.500 --> 34:54.333
Sadly, without a Tonto.

34:55.333 --> 34:58.767
If I were that way inclined,
I'd be after you myself.

34:58.767 --> 35:00.667
And I wouldn't be running.

35:00.667 --> 35:02.767
[ Laughs ]

35:05.133 --> 35:07.667
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

35:18.533 --> 35:20.067
[ Engine starts ]

35:26.533 --> 35:28.833
ELIZABETH: You're lucky
you're not here on a workday.

35:28.833 --> 35:31.067
A cacophony.

35:31.067 --> 35:32.833
When do you see it up
and running?

35:32.833 --> 35:34.433
Two more weeks of renovations,

35:34.433 --> 35:37.800
then the installation of beds
and equipment.

35:37.800 --> 35:40.400
The staffing, of course,
could get under way immediately

35:40.400 --> 35:43.067
if you were to accept my offer.

35:43.067 --> 35:45.167
Oh, I need this.

35:45.167 --> 35:47.067
It does rather take it out
of one.

35:49.100 --> 35:52.067
I admire your intentions.

35:52.067 --> 35:53.233
But?

35:55.600 --> 35:58.400
Do I want to settle for this
or aim higher?

35:59.667 --> 36:01.467
Thank you.

36:01.467 --> 36:03.633
I don't mean to offend.

36:03.633 --> 36:05.600
You don't.

36:07.733 --> 36:09.467
A large hospital
is sniffing around

36:09.467 --> 36:11.100
regarding an
administrative role.

36:13.333 --> 36:15.133
Well, can I offer you
a perspective

36:15.133 --> 36:17.533
-you may not have considered?
-Please.

36:17.533 --> 36:20.433
And I don't mean to offend.

36:21.367 --> 36:23.867
You seem very close
to Harry Polson.

36:24.733 --> 36:26.567
Yes.

36:26.567 --> 36:29.167
Not too personal, I trust?

36:29.167 --> 36:30.600
No.

36:31.233 --> 36:34.067
Henry, we live
in an uncharitable world.

36:34.067 --> 36:38.467
Your liaisons, whether attached
to deep emotion or not,

36:38.467 --> 36:43.167
are seen as sordid and
cause for dismissal elsewhere.

36:44.400 --> 36:47.200
You will always have
a place here

36:47.200 --> 36:50.733
as long as simple discretion
is observed.

36:50.733 --> 36:55.933
Your love will be respected --
if love it becomes or indeed is.

37:01.433 --> 37:02.967
It hadn't occurred to me.

37:04.633 --> 37:08.833
And you will help me
in certain ways as well.

37:10.333 --> 37:12.333
I rest my case.

37:17.700 --> 37:21.367
I'm, uh, locuming for Jack
while he's away.

37:22.800 --> 37:24.300
And then?

37:30.700 --> 37:32.300
Where do I sign?

37:32.300 --> 37:34.667
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

37:37.967 --> 37:40.300
We will do great things
together.

37:40.867 --> 37:42.400
We will.

37:43.400 --> 37:44.967
We will.

37:46.067 --> 37:48.500
[ Music continues ]

37:49.600 --> 37:54.167
I shall be quite bereft
when Ash Park is vacated.

37:54.167 --> 37:56.567
Intimate as I am
with Mrs. Goddard,

37:56.567 --> 38:00.067
I'm even closer
to our dear Mrs. Bligh.

38:00.067 --> 38:02.633
Ah, Doctor.
We'll see you this evening?

38:02.633 --> 38:06.367
What a set we'll be to bid
the old decade adieu, hmm?

38:06.367 --> 38:07.567
Yeah.

38:10.067 --> 38:12.667
He's been like that
since Mrs. Duncan arrived.

38:12.667 --> 38:15.100
Ah.
That bodes ill.

38:16.467 --> 38:17.467
Oh, well.

38:17.467 --> 38:19.300
[ Telephone ringing ]

38:19.300 --> 38:21.667
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

38:24.467 --> 38:26.167
Mama.

38:40.400 --> 38:42.067
David, off you go.

38:42.067 --> 38:44.100
Get ready for dinner.

38:45.067 --> 38:48.167
And if you're very good,
I'll let you stay up late.

38:48.167 --> 38:49.167
Till 12:00?

38:49.167 --> 38:51.367
-Till you see everyone.
-Oh.

38:51.367 --> 38:53.667
-Be a good boy.
-I wouldn't push it.

38:53.667 --> 38:55.500
Bet I can.

38:57.800 --> 38:59.900
Why don't you go
and prepare too?

39:00.500 --> 39:01.833
There's no rush.

39:01.833 --> 39:04.500
Well, Sarah and I have something
to discuss.

39:04.500 --> 39:06.933
-SARAH: Oh, we do?
-Yes.

39:06.933 --> 39:09.633
Well, off you go, then.
You be a good boy.

39:09.633 --> 39:12.400
-Don't you push it.
-[ Laughs ]

39:15.600 --> 39:17.333
It's nothing serious?

39:17.333 --> 39:19.367
Will you shut the door?

39:20.067 --> 39:22.800
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

39:28.300 --> 39:30.967
I was given these yesterday.

39:30.967 --> 39:33.567
The results of my tests.

39:33.567 --> 39:36.300
It's why I popped home
after Christmas.

39:39.433 --> 39:41.600
[ Music continues ]

39:41.600 --> 39:43.633
[ Insects chirping,
clock ticking ]

39:48.533 --> 39:50.267
Happy New Year.

39:54.767 --> 39:57.200
And Elaine says Happy New Year.

39:57.200 --> 39:58.533
Oh, does she?

39:58.533 --> 40:00.200
What a star.

40:00.200 --> 40:02.400
Oh, she's auditioning
for "Tender Vines" next week.

40:02.400 --> 40:03.467
[ Laughs ]

40:03.467 --> 40:06.167
I just heard my name called --
Star.

40:06.167 --> 40:07.767
Oh!

40:07.767 --> 40:09.567
Happy new decade, Anna.

40:09.567 --> 40:11.233
Happy new decade.

40:11.233 --> 40:13.033
Happy new decade.

40:13.033 --> 40:15.100
We'll see you soon.

40:18.400 --> 40:21.933
If I'm a star,
you're a constellation.

40:21.933 --> 40:24.867
Dear, oh, dear, Andrew Swanson.

40:24.867 --> 40:26.933
You will have to do better
than that.

40:26.933 --> 40:28.433
[ Laughs ]

40:28.433 --> 40:30.967
You set the bar high, don't you?

40:30.967 --> 40:32.733
[ Laughs ]

40:35.267 --> 40:37.267
I certainly do.

40:37.267 --> 40:39.633
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

40:45.100 --> 40:46.633
Thank you.

40:49.700 --> 40:52.567
I thought you were done
with complicating your life.

40:53.800 --> 40:56.867
Well, even more
with complicating others.

40:56.867 --> 40:59.767
What point in George knowing?

40:59.767 --> 41:03.567
He would cancel this wonderful
opportunity in Israel

41:03.567 --> 41:05.800
to hover here,
anticipating a death

41:05.800 --> 41:07.700
that will come when it comes.

41:08.700 --> 41:11.400
I may well still be here
when you return,

41:11.400 --> 41:14.800
despite this gloomy prognosis.

41:14.800 --> 41:17.567
You've seemed so robust.

41:19.167 --> 41:22.100
I reserve my energies
for public display.

41:22.100 --> 41:23.967
Any pain?

41:25.433 --> 41:26.833
Niggles.

41:29.200 --> 41:31.067
I wasn't given long years ago,

41:31.067 --> 41:34.800
so I think the old ticker
has done rather well.

41:37.067 --> 41:39.667
Sarah, I watched Douglas fade.

41:40.500 --> 41:43.200
I would rather spare George
the same.

41:44.067 --> 41:45.867
And David.

41:46.900 --> 41:49.300
Let him remember Granny
as she is.

41:52.533 --> 41:56.433
This is to give George
when I'm gone.

41:58.200 --> 41:59.500
If you go.

42:00.433 --> 42:02.667
Evasion doesn't become you.

42:03.733 --> 42:05.400
You're the only one
who'll know of this

42:05.400 --> 42:08.200
until it's impossible
to conceal.

42:08.200 --> 42:09.433
Promise one thing.

42:10.700 --> 42:13.800
If you're clearly fading
and feel that we can reach you,

42:13.800 --> 42:15.567
let us know.

42:18.067 --> 42:19.900
If I'm absolutely sure.

42:22.233 --> 42:24.633
The coward in me...

42:24.633 --> 42:28.933
oh, hopes for an attack
in my sleep.

42:29.767 --> 42:32.967
To close one's eyes
and simply not wake.

42:36.200 --> 42:38.667
It's hard to imagine a world
without you.

42:40.100 --> 42:42.200
Well, it's harder for me.

42:43.667 --> 42:45.500
Do I have your promise?

42:45.500 --> 42:47.933
If it's so important.

42:47.933 --> 42:48.967
It is.

42:52.533 --> 42:54.800
I will miss you.

42:54.800 --> 42:56.567
I'm not talking of Israel.

42:58.900 --> 43:01.667
[ Voice breaking ]
And I you. I'm sorry.

43:03.367 --> 43:06.467
Well, that's why
I'm telling you now.

43:07.600 --> 43:11.933
So that you can be composed
by tonight.

43:13.567 --> 43:18.267
And selfishly, so that I can see
one pair of eyes at midnight

43:18.267 --> 43:20.067
that knows the truth.

43:20.067 --> 43:22.633
I may well cry.

43:22.633 --> 43:25.100
Well, excuse it as tears of joy.

43:28.900 --> 43:30.733
Dear Sarah.

43:34.900 --> 43:36.733
I love you.

43:38.867 --> 43:41.233
I love you.

43:41.233 --> 43:43.433
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

43:49.433 --> 43:52.767
[ Indistinct conversations,
laughter ]

43:52.767 --> 43:55.133
[ Mid-tempo music playing ]

44:00.067 --> 44:01.767
Nearly time, everyone.

44:01.767 --> 44:04.100
Make sure your glasses
are charged.

44:05.733 --> 44:08.900
Emma, Leah, special dispensation
if you wish.

44:08.900 --> 44:10.900
-Really?
-Yes, please.

44:10.900 --> 44:13.767
Well, it's not every night
we enter a new decade.

44:17.533 --> 44:19.367
Would you like me to go
and check?

44:19.367 --> 44:20.700
No.

44:20.700 --> 44:22.433
Um, excuse me.

44:31.733 --> 44:34.267
[ Music playing in distance ]

44:35.133 --> 44:36.533
What?

44:38.467 --> 44:41.433
Well, we can't do it at midnight
in there.

44:50.400 --> 44:52.467
I'm yours.

44:53.067 --> 44:55.100
If you want me.

44:55.633 --> 44:56.900
Totally.

44:56.900 --> 44:58.300
I do.

45:00.700 --> 45:02.533
I do.

45:09.633 --> 45:12.200
[ Indistinct conversations,
insects chirping ]

45:34.867 --> 45:36.700
Thank you.

45:36.700 --> 45:41.500
Thank you for sharing this --
this very special night with us.

45:41.967 --> 45:44.400
A whole new decade ahead.

45:44.400 --> 45:46.667
I know I'm excited.

45:47.233 --> 45:48.433
The possibilities.

45:50.400 --> 45:52.600
And here we go.

45:52.600 --> 45:53.667
-You ready?
-Mm-hmm.

45:55.233 --> 45:56.800
Ten...

45:56.800 --> 45:59.833
...nine...eight...

45:59.833 --> 46:03.767
seven...six...five...

46:03.767 --> 46:07.633
four...three...two...

46:07.633 --> 46:08.933
one!

46:08.933 --> 46:11.267
ALL:
Happy New Year!

46:11.333 --> 46:12.833
ROY:
Happy New Year!

46:12.833 --> 46:14.433
Happy New Year, Mrs. Bligh.

46:14.433 --> 46:16.767
The happiest ever.

46:16.767 --> 46:18.700
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

46:18.700 --> 46:20.533
ELIZABETH:
Happy New Year, my sweet girl.

46:20.533 --> 46:22.800
-Happy New Year, Grandmother.
-Don't cry.

46:23.700 --> 46:26.300
Happy New Year, dear Sarah.

46:26.300 --> 46:27.867
-Likewise.
-Thank you.

46:27.867 --> 46:28.833
Thank you.

46:28.833 --> 46:32.333
Thank you.
I'm so glad you're here.

46:32.333 --> 46:35.467
[ Indistinct conversations,
glasses clinking ]

46:36.800 --> 46:38.800
ROY:
Happy New Year, Mr. Bligh!

46:38.800 --> 46:41.700
[ Music continues ]

46:52.133 --> 46:53.167
My love.

46:56.167 --> 46:57.433
We'll find it.

46:59.067 --> 47:00.633
We will.

47:01.667 --> 47:03.933
-Somehow.
-Somehow.

47:07.167 --> 47:08.067
Forever.

47:12.100 --> 47:14.167
[ Applause ]

47:18.100 --> 47:24.167
* Should auld acquaintance
be forgot *

47:24.167 --> 47:30.500
* And never brought to mind *

47:30.500 --> 47:36.600
* Should auld acquaintance
be forgot *

47:36.600 --> 47:43.067
* And days of auld lang syne *

47:43.067 --> 47:49.767
* For auld lang syne, my dear *

47:49.767 --> 47:55.833
* For auld lang syne *

47:55.833 --> 48:02.300
* We'll take a cup of kindness
yet *

48:02.300 --> 48:09.667
* For days of auld lang syne *

48:09.667 --> 48:11.867
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

48:41.233 --> 48:43.267
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

49:25.067 --> 49:28.133
You have fun, now.
You be good.

49:33.133 --> 49:35.500
[ Music continues ]

50:07.200 --> 50:09.900
Ooh!
Oopsy-daisy!

50:25.067 --> 50:27.800
DAVID: Come on, Daddy!
It's time to go!

50:43.633 --> 50:46.200
[ Birds chirping ]

50:49.133 --> 50:51.833
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

50:58.167 --> 51:01.533
[ Rain falling,
thunder rumbling ]

51:10.867 --> 51:13.067
[ Music continues ]

51:30.733 --> 51:34.433
We met on a ship, you know.

51:37.200 --> 51:40.800
It all began on a ship.

51:44.500 --> 51:49.267
We are the survivors
of that voyage, Olivia.

51:50.300 --> 51:53.567
You, soon, the last.

51:56.500 --> 51:58.567
Dear Leah.

52:03.400 --> 52:05.633
Thank you.

52:10.233 --> 52:13.133
My darling boy.

52:18.800 --> 52:22.867
Who guessed so many would love
my story.

52:27.767 --> 52:30.800
What a wonderful journey.

52:33.200 --> 52:35.900
[ Exhales deeply ]

